&#xa0;
[normal]Supplementary w[bold]ritten evidence submitted by [bold]Oxo[bold]-biodegradable Plastics Association[bold] (OPA)[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Plastics In the marine environment[bold]P[bold]LASTICS IN THE [bold]MARINE ENVIRONMENT[bold]Introduction[bold]“I
[normal]f all the plastic had been made with oxo-biodegradable technology there would be no 
[normal]plastic 
[normal]garbage patches
[normal] 
[normal]in the 
[normal]ocean
[normal]s
[normal].
[normal] ”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In the 
[normal]2012 
[normal]study published in the Marine Pollution Bulletin
[normal]  
[normal]“Occurrence of micro-plastics in
[normal] gastrointestinal tracts of pelagic and demersal fish from the English Channel” it was shown that the majority of pl
[normal]astic particles consumed by the fish
[normal] were rayon (57.8%) and polyester fibres. These are derived from clothes, hygiene products and nappies. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Micro-plastics are not therefore necessarily derived from plastic bags 
[normal]n
[normal]or even from packaging of all types
[normal]- which normally use polyethylene and polypropylene.  Nor have they
[normal] been 
[normal]shown 
[normal]to absorb toxins to any greater extent than other particles in the 
[normal]sea
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Oxo-biodegradable plastics do not contribute to pollution - on the contrary, they are bioassimilated into the bio-background.  This is because the material descends to 
[normal]low molecular-
[normal]weight materials much more quickly than normal plastic.  At that sta
[normal]ge they are no longer plastics and have become biodegradable in the same way as a leaf
[normal] or seaweed
[normal]. They do not therefore float around in the sea for decades absorbing other materials.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]For degradation in the marine environment see report dated 16.8.12 from
[normal] Station d'Essais de Viellissement Naturel de 
[normal]Bandol
[normal], available at
[normal] 
[normal]http://www.biodeg.org/files/uploaded/Bandol%2016.8.12.pdf
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]O
[normal]xo-biodegradable plastics are not intended to deal with
[normal] litter in 
[normal]homes and 
[normal]offices.  They are designed to biodegrade in the open environment when exposed to natural phenomena such as wind, rain, sunlight, etc and to do so in a synergistic relationship to micro-organisms naturally occurring in the open environ
[normal]ment.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The theory of absorption of toxins by micro-plastics is still a theory. At the University of Washington Tacoma seminar (Autumn 2008)
[normal] Prof. Thompson was reported as using the language of opinion rather than fact;-
[normal]“Thompson’s research and various st
[normal]udies have 
[normal]suggested
[normal] that plastic specks in the water column and sediment 
[normal]appear
[normal] to absorb highly toxic and pervasive pollutants, such as PCBs (polychlorinated biphenyls) and pesticides such as DDT (once commonly used to eradicate agricultural and forest p
[normal]ests, and now banned in the United States and other countries). As one 
[normal]theory
[normal] goes, if the oceans’ smallest organisms are dining on plastics dosed up with toxins, then highly concentrated chemicals 
[normal]could possibly
[normal] accumulate up the food chain.”
[normal]Discussion[bold]1-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Polychlorinated biphenyls (PCB) had been widely used globally up until the early 1970’s as additives in many product groups such as plastics, lubricating oils, greases and electrical installations. Their properties of low conductivity, high heat resistance
[normal] and chemical stability has meant that they had been known to persist in the environment, but they have now been banned in many countries. One reason for the ban was the persistence of such toxins in the sea surface micro layer of the marine environment. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The following
[normal] summary review demonstrates that it is highly improbable for oxo-
[normal]bio
[normal]degradable plastic materials to adsorb and accumulate these toxins in the marine environment. 
[normal]Review[bold]3-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Several studies have been 
[normal]done
[normal], including those by Pascall 
[normal]et al,
[normal] Takad
[normal]a 
[normal]et al
[normal], Mato 
[normal]et al
[normal] and Teuten 
[normal]et al
[normal], which demonstrate that 
[normal]conventional 
[normal]polymers such as polyethylene and polypropylene will readily adsorb PCB and other toxins. 
[normal]This is because the polymers are inherently non-
[normal]polar and hydrophobic in nature, 
[normal]and
[normal] with a 
[normal]low Tg (glass transition temperature), their rubbery nature allows for greater segmental mobility, pore-size, free volume, diffusion and partition coefficients. This means that hydrophobic organic toxins such as PCB 
[normal]can
[normal] 
[normal]in theory 
[normal]adsorb to the polymers (th
[normal]rough Van Der Waals attractive forces) from the aqueous environment. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The increased pore-size and free volume also means that 
[normal]if
[normal] the toxin is adsorbed to the polymer, it will not readily desorb, 
[normal]and 
[normal]thus over 
[normal]long 
[normal]periods of time the polymer will  break
[normal] 
[normal]d
[normal]own by shear, friction and weathering, 
[normal]and
[normal] 
[normal]the 
[normal]potential for the plastic material to adsorb 
[normal]toxins is present
[normal]. Takada 
[normal]et al
[normal] demonstrated that in
[normal] a field experiment in Tokyo Bay 
[normal]conventional 
[normal]plastic fragments collected from the bay had 
[normal]adsorbed up to 892 
[normal]ng
[normal]/g. This 
[normal]suggest
[normal]ed
[normal] that t
[normal]he plastic had persisted in that
[normal] area for at least 
[normal]twenty-
[normal]seven years (assuming a linear uptake profile).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Pascall
[normal] et al included polyvinyl chloride and polystyrene in their study. The results from their field experiments demonstrated a significantly lower adsorption uptake of PCB toxin. The difference in chemical structure resulting in differing polarity of the polym
[normal]er, more rigid packing (demonstrated by higher Tg) resulting in restricted segmental mobility, and restricted pore size explains the reduced adsorption observed.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This information helps to build a picture of what would be expected for oxo-
[normal]bio
[normal]degradable pol
[normal]ymer materials. Under the action of oxygen, UV light, and 
[normal]moderate 
[normal]heat, polyethylene and polypropylene containing oxo-
[normal]bio
[normal]degradable additives will change their 
[normal]molecular structure 
[normal]and break down by a mechanism analogous to that shown in Figure 1.
[normal]Figure
[normal] 1, Chiellini, 2
[normal]nd
[normal] CEEES Workshop (2005)
[normal] 
[normal]Confederation of European Environmen
[normal]tal Engineering Societies
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Figure 1 demonstrates how hydroperoxy intermediates are readily formed in the initial phase of degradation, 
[normal]and 
[normal]immediately there is a change in chemica
[normal]l structure and increase in polarity. The formation of these oxygenated species already makes the polymer 
[normal]less attractive to adsorption of
[normal] PCB and related hydrophobic toxins. Lower diffusion and partition coefficients result from increased cohesive forces,
[normal] reducing segmental mobility and pore-size. The highly polar functional groups that are formed
[normal] will not interact with the non-
[normal]polar toxins either through chemical reaction or intermolecular interaction.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The second stage of degradation is the molecular-wei
[normal]ght reduction of the hydroperoxy intermediates (with the vicinal form proceeding more rap
[normal]idly) to 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]9-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]intermediate and short-
[normal]chain aldehydes, ketones, esters, and hydroxyl and hydrocarbon radicals. These will proceed further to carboxylic acids which will be
[normal] readily bioassimilated by 
[normal]micro-
[normal]organisms. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]10-
[normal] 
[normal]In summary the constantly 
[normal]progressing
[normal] chemical breakdown of the polymer results in species with increased hydrophilic character that will readily solubilise and emulsify in the ocean environment. It would, ther
[normal]efore, not be possible for hydrophobic toxins such as PCB to accumulate on oxo-degradable plastic materials
[normal]Conclusion[bold]&#xa0;[bold]11-
[normal] 
[normal]It is 
[normal]sometimes suggested 
[normal]that plastic materials, in particular polyethylene and polypropylene, will adsorb and accumulate hydrophobic toxins that can be found in the sea surface micro layer. 
[normal]However i
[normal]n this 
[normal]review 
[normal]it has been 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]12-
[normal] 
[normal]shown
[normal] that such plastics when treated with additives 
[normal]such as d
[normal]2
[normal]w will change their chemical and physical properties during degradation and that hydrophobic toxins will not be readily 
[normal]ad
[normal]sorbed. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]13-
[normal] 
[normal]There is, therefore, no reason why oxo-
[normal]bio
[normal]degradable plastic materials would provide a route for hydrophobic toxin
[normal] accumulation and the potential to harm marine life
[normal]-
[normal]forms, or provide an entry route for these chemicals into the human food chain. No experimental evidence has been published that links oxo-
[normal]bio
[normal]degradable plastic materials with the accumulation of persiste
[normal]nt hydrophobic toxins in the 
[normal]oceans.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]14-
[normal] 
[normal]Oxo-biodegradable plastics can therefore play a useful role in reducing plastic pollution of the oceans. Indeed if all the plastic had been made with oxo-biodegradable technology there would be no ocean garbage patches
[normal].
[normal]Work[bold] referenced in the Discussion[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Uptake of Polychlorinated Biphenyls (PCBs) from an Aqueous Medium by Polyethylene, Polyvinyl Chloride, and Polystyrene Films.  [bold]MELVIN A. PASCALL, MARY E. ZABIK, MATTHEW J. ZABIK, AND RUBEN J. HERNANDEZ. 
[normal]J. Agric. Food C
[normal]hem.
[normal] 
[normal]2005, [bold]53,
[normal] 164-169. 
[normal]Pellet Watch : Global Monitoring of Persistent Organic Pollutants (POPs) using Beached Plastic Resin Pellets. [bold]HIDESHIGE
[normal] TAKADA, YUKIE MATO, SATOSHI ENDO, REI YAMASHITA, MOHAMAD PAUZI ZAKARIA. 
[normal]www.tuat.ac.jp/~gaia/ipw/documents/takadaproceeding.pdf
