[normal]Dear Mr. Schulz,
[normal]We are very concerned by the assertions in para 5, of the Motion proposed by Mr. Prodi, 
[normal]on a 
[normal]European strategy on plastic waste in the environment (2013/2113(INI))
[normal] 
[normal]which was accepted on 27
[normal]th
[normal] November in the Environment Committee of the Parliament, and is expected to be voted in Plenary on 13
[normal]th
[normal] January.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Paragraph 5 is defamatory of our members and
[normal] their products, and is an unjustified attack on a whole industry which employs very many people.  Members of the Parliament should not be allowed to use their parliamentary protection from legal action to 
[normal]commit defamation, and it is for that reason that 
[normal]we are bringing this to your attention as President.
[normal]  I trust that Members will have the opportunity to reconsider this ill-advised paragraph in Plenary, and to consider a motion to amend it which I understand will be made.
[normal]There is no evidence that oxo-bi
[normal]odegradable plastic is ‘dangerous’ nor that it is ‘disruptive to human health’ or the environment, nor that it contains heavy metals. 
[normal]T
[normal]he scientific evidence
[normal] 
[normal]is
[normal] that oxo-biodegradable plastic 
[normal](as distinct from bio-based plastic) 
[normal]does not
[normal] make recycling pr
[normal]ocesses more difficult
[normal]. 
[normal]These claims, which are central to the Motion, are false and seriously misleading.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There is no evidence in the Commission’s Green Paper on plastic waste in the environment to support these allegations
[normal]In 
[normal]February 2011 a Life Cycle
[normal] Assessment
[normal] by Intertek was published by the UK Environment Agency which shows that oxo-biodegradable plastic bags have a better LCA than paper bags or compostable plastic bags.  In May 2012 a further LCA by Intertek
[normal] included the litter metric and compar
[normal]ed oxo-biodegradable plastic with bio-based plastic and conventional plastic.  It put oxo ahead in its potential to reduce the plastic waste problem and its less harmful impact on the environment and on global warming.    In its ability to reduce plastic l
[normal]itter, oxo-bio scored 75% better than conventional plastic, and bio-based plastics were worse than oxo in all 11 environmental impact categories.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Oxo-biodegradation causes the plastic to convert at the end of its useful life in the presence of oxygen into
[normal] a biodegradable material.  
[normal]This process has been studied in depth at the Technical Research Institute of Sweden and the Swedish University of Agricultural Scienc
[normal]es, and a
[normal] peer-reviewed report of the work was published in Vol
[normal].
[normal] 96 of the journal of Polymer 
[normal]Degradation &amp; Stability (2011) at page 919-928.  It shows 91% biodegradation in a soil environment within 24 months, in accordance with ISO 17556
[normal] and it does NOT therefore leave fragments of plastic in the environment. The fragments found in the oceans, an
[normal]d those found to have been ingested by birds and fish are fragments of ordinary plastic.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Oxo-biodegradable plastic does NOT contain heavy metals.  It is designed so that it will NOT degrade in anaerobic conditions and will NOT therefore generate methane.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There is no justification for the claim that ox
[normal]o-biodegradable plastics should 
[normal]be phased out of the market or banned outright, as soon as possible before 2020 or at all.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Yours sincerely,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
